g.text: Block Matching - Pipeline
1. Choose a disparity range [0,D]
It determines how close an object
is to the camera.
2. For all pixels x = (x,y) compute the best disparity
3. Do this for both images and apply left-right
consistency check to remove outliers
Block Matching - Limitations
Half occlusion
Some regions are visible in an image
and not visible in the other image
It will be rendered through a dark region!
Assumptions violations
Block matching assumes that all pixels inside the window are displaced
by d. However, this assumption (fronto-parallel assumption) is often violated
It holds only true for 3D planes in the scene parallel to the image plane.
In fact, slanted surfaces deform perspectively when the viewpoint changes
Window size
Small window size lead to matching ambiguities and noise in the
disparity max
Large windows lead to smoother results, but loss of detailts
and border bleeding
Left-Right Consistency Test
Outliers and half occlusions can be detected via a left-right
consistency test
It computes the disparity map for both images, and verify if
they map to each other (cycle)
For every pixel in the left image, we look at
the disparity and move along the disparity in
the right image
Then we query the disparity at that location.
Finally we move backwards, and the point in which
we end with, should be the same as the one in
which we started! If not, we reject that point
This happen with occlusions!
